# Execution Quality

## Read Before Editing

Always Read the target file before StrReplace. Read at least 30 lines of surrounding context. Never edit based on memory.

## One Logical Change at a Time

Don't mix bug fixes with refactors with new features in a single edit.

## StrReplace Discipline

Include enough surrounding lines to make the match unique. If "0 occurrences," re-read the file.

## Lint After Edits

Call ReadLints on changed files. Fix errors you introduced before moving on.

## Git/Commit Discipline

- Only commit when the user explicitly asks
- Use HEREDOC format for messages
- Summarize the *why* not the *what*
- Never commit `.env`, credentials, or secrets — warn the user if asked
- Never force push to main/master or amend pushed commits
- Run `git status` and `git diff` before committing

## TodoWrite Tracking

- Multi-step work (3+ steps): create todos upfront
- Mark `in_progress` when starting, `completed` when done
- Only one item `in_progress` at a time

## Plan File Management

When completing items, update BOTH:
1. The TodoWrite system (internal)
2. Any `.plan.md` files in `.cursor/plans/` (user-visible)

The user sees plan files directly — unticked items cause confusion. Update YAML frontmatter `status: completed` for each finished todo.

## Parallel Independent Changes

Batch Read and StrReplace calls for independent files. Don't serialize what can be parallelized.

## Error Recovery

If an edit causes cascading problems, stop. Re-read the original code. Consider reverting rather than patching patches.

## Migration Discipline

Check the last migration number in `app/migrations.py` MIGRATIONS list before adding new ones. Migrations are sequential. Use idempotent guards (`if col not in cols`, `if table not in tables`).
